x4freetext: Triton and alpha-particle production in neutron-induced
reactions on carbon at En=42.5,62.7 and 72.8 MeV

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.53, p.1309 (1996)

x4freetext: The accelerated proton beam is focused on a
natural lithium target. A quasimonoenergetic neutron
beam was produced at 0 degr. lab. angle. Using a
3-mm-thick lithium target and a 10**(-5)A proton beam,
about 10**6 n/s are available at the location of
reaction chamber (around 3m downstream from the
lithium target).

x4codes.hlp: Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: Four charged-particle detector telescopes are
used simultaneosly. Each of them consists of a delta-E
detector (NE102 pl.scin., 0.1 mm thick, 4cm in diam.)
viewed by an XP2020 photomultiplier via lucite light
guide, and an E detector (CsI(Tl) crystal, 22 mm thick
38.2mm in diam.), viewed by an XP2262B photomultiplier.
For energy calibration of the detectors the protons and
deuterons recoiling from a polypropylene (1 or 0.5 mm
thick) and a 0.6-mm-thick deuterated polypropylene targ
respectively, are used.
The neutron-beam radial distribution measured
with NE102 scin. ( 5mm in diam.)
An elemental carbon target (5x5 cm2 surface and 1 mm
thick). The angle of the target with the beam was
chosen to minimize the thickness of the target material
traversed the produced charged particles towards
telescopes.
The beam monitoring system is realized in two ways.
Behind the lithium target, the incident proton beam is
deflected by a magnetic dipole into a water-cooled
Faraday cup which serves as beam minitor.
Second: The integral of the recoil proton peak. A
charged particle telescope detects at 45 degr.
the H(n,p) scattered protons. It consists of a NE102
(2-mm-thick) scin. as delta-E ans a CsI(Tl) crystal as
E detector.
The uncertainty of the cross section absolute
scale.
5%- the measured reference (n,p) cross sections
2%- beam monitoring
2%- statistics in the H(n,p) recoil proton peak
1%- solid-angle corrections
Relative error
